  <section class="bio-section" id="origin">
    <div class="bio-section-head">§ 01 · Origin</div>
    <h2>Born of the Lineage. Schooled in the Corridor.</h2>

    <p>Israel Lee Armstead was born and raised in Liberty City, Miami — the same corridor that produced the grievances, the resistance, and now the remedy that E5 Enclave was built to deliver.</p>

    <p>He graduated from <strong>Charles R. Drew K–8 Center</strong> in 2001 — a school where his grand-uncle, Ralph McCartney, served as a security guard during Israel's years in those halls. That fact is not footnoted. It is the foundation: a man guarding the door of a school that would one day bear his name, in a neighborhood where his nephew's nephew would grow up to build the institution that honors them both.</p>

    <p>He attended <strong>Miami Northwestern Senior High School</strong> on the Gifted track, graduating in 2005 — the same school district, the same pipeline gap, the same Liberty City that the McCartney Academy is being built to close.</p>

    <p>Before his career began in earnest, Israel was elected <strong>National Parliamentarian</strong> of his faith tradition's Youth Outreach Council at age eleven. At fifteen he served on the Usher's Board, Nurses Guild, and Vestry Board. At sixteen, he was a voting delegate to the African Orthodox Church's General Synod. The instinct for institution-building was not cultivated — it was native.</p>

    <div class="bio-pull">
      <blockquote>"The center holds. The work is underway."</blockquote>
      <cite>— E5 Enclave Founding Doctrine</cite>
    </div>
  </section>

