  <!-- ═══ § 03 — THE FOUNDING ═════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="bio-section" id="founding">
    <div class="bio-section-head">§ 03 · The Founding</div>
    <h2>The Institution the Work Has Always Needed.</h2>

    <p>E5 Enclave Incorporated was filed on June 30, 2024, in the state of Florida, as a nonprofit public charity. Israel is its founder, president, and chief visionary — and the architect of every structural decision made since inception.</p>

    <p>The organizing logic is the Five Pillars: Environmental, Economic, Educational, Engagement, and Emancipated — a deliberate structure that mirrors the shape of the harm and names the shape of the remedy. Three centuries of unrecorded obligation became the blueprint. The Pillars became the plan.</p>

    <p>On April 11, 2026, E5 Enclave declared itself the <strong>world's first agentic-first staffed nonprofit</strong> — an institution where AI agents operating under human direction produce institutional-scale output from a deliberately lean team built to outlast cycles. The model is not a novelty. It is a doctrine.</p>

    <p>The flagship programs under Israel's direction include <strong>Lineage Farms / FarmBlock</strong> (cooperative urban agriculture with blockchain governance), <strong>McCartney Academy</strong> (a K–12 private school in foundation phase, named in honor of Ralph McCartney), <strong>Block to the Boardroom</strong> (the pipeline from neighborhood organizing to policy authorship), and <strong>Restitution 246</strong> (the documented obligations of emancipation as a policy campaign).</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ═══ § 04 — LINEAGE WORK ══════════════════════════════════ -->
  <section class="bio-section" id="lineage">
    <div class="bio-section-head">§ 04 · Lineage Work</div>
    <h2>Forensic Genealogy at Institutional Scale.</h2>

    <p>Israel is the subject of <a href="/about/forensic-genealogy/">E5 Enclave's benchmark genealogical case file</a> — a complete evidentiary record tracing six confirmed generations from Liberty City, Miami to the chattel slavery of antebellum Clarke County, Alabama. The file meets the Genealogical Proof Standard (GPS) established by the Board for Certification of Genealogists.</p>

    <p>The case file identifies <strong>Benjamin Armstead</strong>, born 1838, enslaved in Clarke County, Alabama — documented in the 1842 probate inventory of Capt. William Armistead. Six intervening generations connect Benjamin to Israel through primary-source census, vital, and court records. The chain of custody holds at every link.</p>

    <p>That case file is now the proof of work for a forensic genealogy pipeline capable of producing GPS-standard case files in 90 minutes for tribal enrollment, citizenship, probate, reparations eligibility, and beyond. The pipeline was built because Israel needed it first — and because he understood that what one family needs is what thousands of families need.</p>

