    <div class="bio-section-head">§ 05 · Governance &amp; Public Service</div>
    <h2>Institutional Service Began Before His Career.</h2>

    <p>Israel's leadership record in governance began in his youth. At eleven, he was elected national parliamentarian of his faith tradition's Youth Outreach Council. At fifteen, he served concurrently on the Usher's Board, Nurses Guild, and Vestry Board. At sixteen, he served as a voting delegate to the African Orthodox Church General Synod.</p>

    <p>He is a current Candidacy Member and former elected General Councilor of the <strong>Urantia Book Fellowship</strong> — one of a small number of individuals elected to represent that international readership body.</p>

    <p>His grand-uncle, <strong>Ralph McCartney</strong>, served on the Miami-Dade County Public Schools board committee that watched Booker T. Washington High School phased out of existence. He gave oral history to the University of Florida's Samuel Proctor Oral History Program on August 14, 1997. Congresswoman Frederica Wilson knew him personally. The Educational pillar's flagship academy bears his name — and Israel is the reason it will be built in the same Liberty City corridor where Ralph stood guard.</p>
  </section>

